name: Confucius
bio: Confucius was a Chinese philosopher and politician of the Spring and Autumn period. The philosophy of Confucius, also known as Confucianism, emphasized personal and governmental morality, correctness of social relationships, justice, kindness, and sincerity.

name: Britney Spears
bio: Britney Jean Spears is an American singer, songwriter, dancer, and actress. She is credited with influencing the revival of teen pop during the late 1990s and early 2000s, for which she is referred to as the "Princess of Pop".

name: Joey Schweitzer
bio: Joey Schweitzer is a YouTube creator. He talks about life improvement, work optimisation and social among other topics.

name: Josh Wheeler
bio: Josh Wheeler is a fictional character in Daybreak TV series, where he's a lone survivor seeking his girlfriend in the post-apocalyptic landscape.

name: Lucie (makesens)
bio: Lucie animates the french podcast Paumé_e_s.

name: Madelaine de Montargis
bio: Madelaine de Montargis is a fictional character in the TV series "La Révolution" and played by Amélia Lacquemant. She's Elise's little sister and has the particularity to be muted. She often has nightmares.

name: Verna
bio: Verna is a shape-shifter and mysterious woman who proposed a deal to Roderick & Madeline Usher.

name: Lucy
bio: Lucy is a fictional character played by Jessie Buckley in the film "i'm thinking of ending things". She's new Jake's girlfriend and takes a trip with him to meet his parents.

name: Wayne Gretzky
bio: Wayne Douglas Gretzky CC is a Canadian former professional ice hockey player and former head coach. He played 20 seasons in the National Hockey League for four teams from 1979 to 1999.

name: Carl Gustav Jung
bio: Carl Gustav Jung, originally Karl Gustav Jung, was a Swiss psychiatrist and psychoanalyst who founded analytical psychology. Jung's work has been influential in the fields of psychiatry, anthropology, archaeology, literature, philosophy, and religious studies.

name: Helen Keller
bio: Helen Adams Keller was an American author, political activist, and lecturer. She was the first deaf-blind person to earn a Bachelor of Arts degree.

name: Jean Giraudoux
bio:
Hippolyte Jean Giraudoux was a French novelist, essayist, diplomat and playwright. He is considered among the most important French dramatists of the period between World War I and World War II.

His work is noted for its stylistic elegance and poetic fantasy. Giraudoux's dominant theme is the relationship between man and woman—or in some cases, between man and some unattainable ideal.
job: French novelist, essayist, diplomat and playwright

name: George Nakai
bio: George Nakai is a sculptor and Amy's stay-at-home husband. He's played by Joseph Lee in the TV limited series BEEF created by Lee Sung Jin.

name: Tony Robbins
bio: Anthony Jay Robbins is an American author, life coach, and philanthropist. Robbins is known for his infomercials, seminars, and self-help books including the books Unlimited Power and Awaken the Giant Within. In 2015 and 2016 Robbins was listed on the Worth Magazine Power 100 list.

name: Achilles (Achille)
bio: In Greek mythology, Achilles or Achilleus was a hero of the Trojan War, the greatest of all the Greek warriors, and is the central character of Homer's Iliad. He was the son of the Nereid Thetis and Peleus, king of Phthia.

name: Pauline Marionnet
bio: Pauline Marionnet is a fictional character in the french book "Le parfum du bonheur est plus fort sous la pluie" having difficulties with her life. She went back to live with her parents with her child after some events with her husband.

name: Howard Salomon
bio: Howard Salomon is a fictional character played by Bill Camp in the TV miniseries The Outsider. He's the lawyer of Glory Maitland.

name: Peter Singer
bio: Peter Albert David Singer AC is an Australian moral philosopher. He is the Ira W. DeCamp Professor of Bioethics at Princeton University, and a Laureate Professor at the Centre for Applied Philosophy and Public Ethics at the University of Melbourne.

name: Frank Sinatra
bio: Francis Albert Sinatra was an American singer, actor and producer who was one of the most popular and influential musical artists of the 20th century. He is one of the best-selling music artists of all time, having sold more than 150 million records worldwide.

name: Kenneth Hayes
bio: Kenneth Hayes is a fictional character played by Michael Esper in the TV miniseries The Outsider. He is a legal prosecutor.

name: Dirty Biology
bio: Science videos on mind fuck and fun subjects.

name: Clausen
bio: Clausen is a fictional character played by Sylvester Groth in the TV series "Dark". He arrives in the second season as an investigator assisting Charlotte and the police force.

name: Dr. Karl Landy
bio: Dr. Karl Landy is Anna's psychiatrist in the film The Woman in the Window. He's played by Tracy Letts.

name: Pablo Picasso
bio: Pablo Ruiz Picasso was a Spanish painter, sculptor, printmaker, ceramicist, stage designer, poet and playwright who spent most of his adult life in France.

name: Jesper Juul
bio: Jesper Juul is a Danish game designer, educator, and theorist in the field of video game studies. He is an associate professor at the Danish Design School. Juul is co-editor, with William Uricchio and Geoffrey Long, of the MIT Press Playful Thinking series.

name: Isabelle "Izzy" Silva
bio: A graduate student in psychology and escort girl in the TV series You Me Her.

name: Henry Wadsworth Longfellow
bio: Henry Wadsworth Longfellow was an American poet and educator whose works include "Paul Revere's Ride", The Song of Hiawatha, and Evangeline. He was the first American to translate Dante Alighieri's Divine Comedy and was one of the Fireside Poets from New England.

name: Amanda Knox
bio: Amanda Knox is an exoneree, journalist, public speaker, and author of the New York Times best-selling memoir, Waiting to Be Heard (HarperCollins, April 2013). Between 2007 and 2015, she spent nearly four years in an Italian prison and eight years on trial for a murder she didn’t commit. The controversy over Amanda’s case made international headlines for nearly a decade, and thrust her into the spotlight, where she was vilified and shamed. Amanda now works to shed light on the issues of wrongful conviction, truth seeking, and public shaming, and to inspire people towards empathy and perspective.

name: Paul Fussel
bio: Paul Fussell, Jr. was an American cultural and literary historian, author and university professor. His writings cover a variety of topics, from scholarly works on eighteenth-century English literature to commentary on America's class system.

name: Michel de Montaigne
bio: Michel Eyquem de Montaigne, Lord of Montaigne was one of the most significant philosophers of the French Renaissance, known for popularizing the essay as a literary genre. His work is noted for its merging of casual anecdotes and autobiography with intellectual insight.

name: Tennessee Williams
bio: Thomas Lanier Williams III, known by his pen name Tennessee Williams, was an American playwright and screenwriter. Along with contemporaries Eugene O'Neill and Arthur Miller, he is considered among the three foremost playwrights of 20th-century American drama.

name: Joseph Campbell
bio: Joseph John Campbell was an American professor of literature at Sarah Lawrence College who worked in comparative mythology and comparative religion. His work covers many aspects of the human experience.

name: Rya Goodwin
bio:
Rya Goodwin – played by Amanda Seyfried – is an investigator in the TV series The Crowded Room.

She gets Danny to slowly unveil his past through a serie of interviews.

name: Émile Gravier
bio: Émile Gravier is a fictional character from the french movie "La Cité de la peur", played by Sam Karmann.

name: La chaîne de P.A.U.L
bio: La chaîne de P.A.U.L is a french YouTube channel making documentary about celebrities or fictional characters like the Joker, Emma Watson and Orelsan.

name: Vera Molnar
bio:
Vera Molnár (born 1924) is a Hungarian media artist living and working in France. Molnar is widely considered to be a pioneer of computer art and generative art, and is also one of the first women to use computers in her art practice.

Born in Hungary, she studied aesthetics and art history at the Hungarian University of Fine Arts. In the 1940s and 50s, she created non-representational paintings. By 1959 she was making combinatorial images; in 1968, she would use a computer to create her first algorithmic drawings.

In the 1960s, she founded two groups in France concerned with the use of technology within the arts: the Groupe de Recherche d’Art Visuel and Art et Informatique. In 1976 took place her first solo exhibition in the gallery of the London Polytechnic.

name: Bill Parrish
bio: Bill Parrish if a fictional character played by Anthony Hopkins in the film "Meet Joe Black".

name: Christopher Columbus
bio: Christopher Columbus was an Italian explorer and colonizer who completed four voyages across the Atlantic Ocean that opened the New World for conquest and permanent European colonization of the Americas.

name: Oprah Winfrey
bio: Oprah Gail Winfrey is an American media executive, actress, talk show host, television producer, and philanthropist.

name: Marques Brownlee
bio: Also known professionally as MKBHD, he is an American YouTuber, best known for his technology-focused videos.

name: Aristotle
bio: Aristotle was a Greek philosopher and polymath during the Classical period in Ancient Greece. He was the founder of the Lyceum and the Peripatetic school of philosophy and Aristotelian tradition. Along with his teacher Plato, he has been called the "Father of Western Philosophy".

name: Zdzisław Beksiński
bio: Zdzisław Beksiński was a Polish painter, photographer and sculptor, specializing in the field of dystopian surrealism. Beksiński made his paintings and drawings in what he called either a 'Baroque' or a 'Gothic' manner. His creations were made mainly in two periods.

name: Marie Adler
bio: Marie Adler is a fictional character which is a victim of sexual assault in the American miniseries Unbelievable.

name: Maud Ankaoua
bio:
Maud Ankaoua, born October 23, 1971, is a French financial advisor and writer.

In 2017, Maud Ankaoua signed her first novel, Kilomètre zéro : Le chemin du bonheur, inspired by her personal story. At the request of her best friend, the main character, Maëlle, financial director of a start-up, puts her daily life on hold to complete an ascent of Annapurna,.

Passionate about human relationships, the author devotes herself to feel-good literature about personal well-being and the quest for self.

In Plus jamais sans moi, published in 2023, the heroine sets off on a journey of self-discovery, this time on the roads to Santiago de Compostela.

name: Paul Theroux
bio: Paul Edward Theroux is an American travel writer and novelist, whose best-known work is The Great Railway Bazaar. He has published numerous works of fiction, some of which were adapted as feature films.

name: Jake
bio: Jake is a fictional character played by Jesse Plemons in the film "i'm thinking of ending things". He's Lucy's boyfriend and plan to go visit his parent on their farm.

name: Anne Lamott
bio: Anne Lamott is an American novelist and non-fiction writer. She is also a progressive political activist, public speaker, and writing teacher. Lamott is based in Marin County, California. Her nonfiction works are largely autobiographical.

name: Françoise Bertin
bio: Françoise Bertin was a French actress. She appeared in over 125 films since 1961. Among these were five films directed by Alain Resnais: Last Year at Marienbad, Muriel, The War Is Over, I Want to Go Home, and Same Old Song. Born in Paris on 23 September 1925, she died in Galan, Hautes-Pyrénées, on 26 October 2014.

name: Rosa Parks
bio: Rosa Louise McCauley Parks was an American activist in the civil rights movement best known for her pivotal role in the Montgomery bus boycott. The United States Congress has called her "the first lady of civil rights" and "the mother of the freedom movement".

name: The Nerdwriter
bio: The Nerdwriter is a weekly video essay series that puts ideas to work.

name: Christopher Nolan
bio: Christopher Edward Nolan CBE is a British-American filmmaker known for making personal, distinctive films within the Hollywood mainstream. His directorial efforts have grossed more than US$5 billion worldwide, garnered 34 Oscar nominations and ten wins.

name: Douglas Adams
bio: Douglas Noel Adams was an English author, screenwriter, essayist, humorist, satirist and dramatist. Adams was author of The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy, which originated in 1978 as a BBC radio comedy before developing into a "trilogy" of five books that sold more than 15 million copies in his lifetime and generated a television series, several stage plays, comics, a video game, and in 2005 a feature film.

name: Darth Vader
bio: Darth Vader is a Sith Lord and the father of Luke Skywalker.

name: Henri Bergson
bio: Henri-Louis Bergson was a French philosopher, who was influential in the traditions of analytic philosophy and continental philosophy, especially during the first half of the 20th century until the Second World War, but also after 1966 when Gilles Deleuze published Le Bergsonisme.

name: Father
bio: David Thewlis is an English actor (among other jobs) playing Jake's father in the film "i'm thinking of ending things".

name: Homer Simpson
bio: Homer Simpson is the bumbling husband of Marge and father to Bart, Lisa, and Maggie.

name: Emma Green
bio: Emma Green is a fictional character played by Hilary Swank in the TV series Away. In the show, she's a NASA astronaut who is commander of the mission and ship Atlas.

name: Patrick Bialès
bio: Commissaire Patrick Bialès is a fictional character in the french movie "La Cité de la peur" played by Gérard Darmon.

name: Angelica Green
bio: Angelica Green is a fictional character in the Daybreak TV series, where she is a 10 year old genius with mild pyromania.

name: Bob Marley
bio: Robert Nesta Marley, OM was a Jamaican singer, songwriter, and musician. Considered one of the pioneers of reggae, his musical career was marked by fusing elements of reggae, ska, and rocksteady, as well as his distinctive vocal and songwriting style.

name: Pema Chödrön
bio: Pema Chödrön is an American Tibetan-Buddhist. She is an ordained nun, former acharya of Shambhala Buddhism and disciple of Chögyam Trungpa Rinpoche. Chödrön has written several dozen books and audiobooks, and is principal teacher at Gampo Abbey in Nova Scotia.

name: Ian Bogost
bio: Ian Bogost is an American academic and video game designer. He holds a joint professorship in the School of Literature, Media, and Communication and in Interactive Computing in the College of Computing at the Georgia Institute of Technology, where he is the Ivan Allen College of Liberal Arts Distinguished Chair in Media Studies.

name: Maurits Cornelis Escher
bio: Maurits Cornelis Escher was a Dutch graphic artist who made mathematically inspired woodcuts, lithographs, and mezzotints. Despite wide popular interest, Escher was for long somewhat neglected in the art world, even in his native Netherlands. He was 70 before a retrospective exhibition was held.

name: Paul Cho
bio: Danny's unmotivated younger brother. He likes video-games. This character is played by Young Mazino in the TV limited series BEEF, created by Lee Sung Jin.

name: Rue Bennett
bio: Rue Bennett is a fictional character played by Zendaya in the TV series Euphoria. In the series, she's a recovering teenage drug addict struggling to find her place in the world.

name: Thomas J. Watson
bio: Thomas John Watson Sr. was an American businessman. He served as the chairman and CEO of International Business Machines. He oversaw the company's growth into an international force from 1914 to 1956. Watson developed IBM's management style and corporate culture from John Henry Patterson's training at NCR.

name: Issac Asimov
bio:
Isaac Asimov was an American writer and professor of biochemistry at Boston University. During his lifetime, Asimov was considered one of the "Big Three" science fiction writers, along with Robert A. Heinlein and Arthur C. Clarke. A prolific writer, he wrote or edited more than 500 books. He also wrote an estimated 90,000 letters and postcards.

- Isaac Asimov was born in Petrovichi, Russia (now part of Belarus) on January 2, 1920. His family immigrated to the United States when he was 3 years old.

- He taught himself to read at age 5 and was a voracious reader from a young age, devouring the science fiction magazines sold at his family's candy stores in Brooklyn.

- Asimov earned a PhD in biochemistry from Columbia University in 1948 and worked as a professor of biochemistry at Boston University for many years.

- He was one of the most prolific writers of all time, authoring or editing over 500 books across genres like science fiction, mysteries, and popular science. His most famous works are the Foundation and Robot series.

- Asimov coined the term "robotics" and developed the Three Laws of Robotics which have become hugely influential in science fiction and real-world robotics.

- He won numerous awards including multiple Hugo and Nebula Awards for his science fiction writing.

- Asimov was an atheist and a prominent member of the humanist movement, serving as president of the American Humanist Association from 1985 until his death in 1992.

- He had a fear of flying and did so only twice in his life, preferring to travel by ship or train.

- Asimov died in New York City on April 6, 1992 at age 72 from heart and kidney failure, complicated by HIV contracted from a blood transfusion.
job: American writer and professor of biochemistry

name: Jean Massiet
bio: Jean Massiet is a french political reporter who created Accropolis, a political news live stream. He worked with known politicians like Marisol Touraine, and at "La Ville de Paris". Youth and popular education activist, he wants to democratize politics to help people better understand the news. He's also passionate about video games and web culture.

name: Bob Dylan
bio: Bob Dylan is an American singer-songwriter, author, and visual artist who has been a major figure in popular culture for more than fifty years.

name: Sheryl Sandberg
bio: Sheryl Kara Sandberg is an American technology executive, author, and billionaire. She is the chief operating officer of Facebook and founder of LeanIn.Org. In June 2012, she was elected to Facebook's board of directors by existing board members, becoming the first woman to serve on its board.

name: Jacques Henriot
bio: Jacques Henriot is a french wirter and author of the book "Sous couleur de jouer". His book analyzes video games through psychology and the "gamification" concept.

name: Rolf Potts
bio: Rolf Potts is an American travel writer, essayist, podcaster, and author. He has written four books, including Vagabonding, Marco Polo Didn't Go There, and Souvenir. His travel writing has appeared in National Geographic Traveler, Outside, Salon.com, Slate.com, The Guardian, and World Hum.

name: Jada Pinkett Smith
bio: Jada Koren Pinkett Smith is an American actress, screenwriter, producer, talk show host, businesswoman, and an occasional singer-songwriter. She began her acting career in 1990, with a guest appearance on the short-lived sitcom True Colors, and subsequently starred in the television series A Different World.

name: Sypha Belnades
bio: Sypha Belnades is a Speaker Magician and the Elder's granddaughter who wields powerful elemental magic. She travels with Trevor Belmont.

name: Ponce
bio: Ponce, also known as the flowers king, is a french Twitch streamer. He plays various video games like Mario Kart, Zelda or Outer Wilds. On mondays, he organizes culture games with his viewers.

name: Jacques-Bénigne Bossuet
bio: Jacques-Bénigne Lignel Bossuet was a French bishop and theologian, renowned for his sermons and other addresses. He has been considered by many to be one of the most brilliant orators of all time and a masterly French stylist.

name: Forrest Gump
bio: Forrest Gump is a 1994 American comedy-drama film directed by Robert Zemeckis and written by Eric Roth. It is an adaptation of the 1986 novel of the same name by Winston Groom, and stars Tom Hanks, Robin Wright, Gary Sinise, Mykelti Williamson, and Sally Field.

name: Lola Guilldou
bio: Lola is a french game designer, graphic designer, content creator on YouTube and Twitch. She's the author of the game Puppy Cross, a pycross game with dogs. She also gives talks at conferences.

name: Hilda Spellman
bio: Hildegarde Antoinette "Hilda" Spellman is a character featured in the Archie comic book Sabrina the Teenage Witch. In the Netflix TV series, she's played by Lucy Davis. Hilda is a full witch (as opposed to half or fully mortal) who lives in the fictional town of Greendale (in the 1990s live-action sitcom, Hilda lives in fictional Westbridge, Massachusetts). Hilda lives with her niece Sabrina Spellman, sister Zelda Spellman, and the family cat Salem, a former witch turned into a cat as punishment for his attempt at world domination.

name: Woody Allen
bio: Heywood "Woody" Allen is an American director, writer, actor, and comedian whose career spans more than six decades. He began his career as a comedy writer in the 1950s, writing jokes and scripts for television and publishing several books of short humor pieces.

name: Graham
bio: Graham Simpkins is a fictional character played by Jude Law in the film "The Holiday".

name: Steven Pressfield
bio: Steven Pressfield is an American author of historical fiction, non-fiction, and screenplays.

name: Stephen R. Covey
bio: Stephen Richards Covey was an American educator, author, businessman, and keynote speaker. His most popular book is The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People.

name: Albert Einstein
bio: Albert Einstein was a German-born theoretical physicist who developed the theory of relativity, one of the two pillars of modern physics. His work is also known for its influence on the philosophy of science.

name: Oka
bio: Okka is a fictional character played by Doudou Masta in the TV series "La Révolution". In the show, he's a prisoner and reveals some information to Joseph Guillotin.

name: Claude Lévi-Strauss
bio:
Claude Lévi-Strauss was a French anthropologist and ethnologist whose work was key in the development of the theories of structuralism and structural anthropology. 

He held the chair of Social Anthropology at the Collège de France between 1959 and 1982, was elected a member of the Académie française in 1973 and was a member of the School for Advanced Studies in the Social Sciences in Paris. He received numerous honours from universities and institutions throughout the world.

name: Christophe Castaner
bio: Christophe Castaner is a French politician who has been serving as the Minister of the Interior since 16 October 2018 and as the Executive Officer of La République En Marche! since 2017.
job: Minister of the Interior of France

name: Paula Poundstone
bio: Paula Poundstone is an American stand-up comedian, author, actress, interviewer, and commentator. Beginning in the late 1980s, she performed a series of one-hour HBO comedy specials. She provided backstage commentary during the 1992 presidential election on The Tonight Show with Jay Leno.

name: Robert J. Hanlon
bio: Robert J. Hanlon is an author.

name: Talluha "Tully" Hart
bio: Talluha "Tully" Hart, is a fictional character played by Katherine Heigl in the streaming TV series "Firefly Lane". In the show, she's a famous host of a daytime talk show known as The Girlfriend Hour.

name: Anne Barratin
bio:
Anne Marie Louise Godillon, known as Anne Barratin, born on October 4, 1832 and died on December 14, 1915, was a French philanthropist and woman of letters.

A member of the Société des gens de lettres and Officer of the Palmes académiques, Anne Barratin is best known for her thoughts and aphorisms. She has also written poems and song lyrics. The philosophy behind her works is summed up in the preface to Chemin faisant, her first book: "To study man, to seek to know him better, is not to condemn oneself to love him less, it is to learn to pity him in all his failings, to excuse him in many of his errors, to judge more closely the difficulties of the struggle, and to account to him for his efforts".

name: Jérôme Keinborg
bio: Video producer @nowtechtv. French but US childhood. Web video Consultant production.

name: Sir Claus Moser
bio: Claus Adolf Moser, Baron Moser, KCB, CBE was a British statistician who made major contributions in both academia and the Civil Service.

name: Marie-Louise von Franz
bio: Marie-Louise von Franz was a Swiss Jungian psychologist and scholar, known for her psychological interpretations of fairy tales and of alchemical manuscripts.

name: Etienne de La Boétie
bio: Étienne or Estienne de La Boétie was a French judge, writer and "a founder of modern political philosophy in France". He is best remembered as the great and close friend of the eminent essayist Michel de Montaigne "in one of history's most notable friendships", as well as an earlier influence for anarchist thought.

name: The Cowboy
bio: He gives advices and warnings to Justin Theroux after he quits his job. The Cowboy is a fictional character played by the actor Monty Montgomery.

name: Samuel Beckett
bio: Samuel Barclay Beckett was an Irish novelist, playwright, short story writer, theatre director, poet, and literary translator. A resident of Paris for most of his adult life, he wrote in both French and English.

name: Tai Lopez
bio: Tai Lopez is an investor, partner, or advisor to over 20 multi-million dollar businesses. Through his popular book club and podcasts Tai shares advice on how to achieve health, wealth, love, and happiness with 1.4 million people in 40 countries.

name: Sister Mary
bio: Sister Mary alias Shotgun Mary is a fictional character played by Toya Turner in the TV series Warrior Nun.

name: Arnaud (Stupid Economics)
bio: Arnaud (Stupid Economics) is a french YouTuber talking about economy. He's the main host on the YouTube channel "Stupid Economics" and does live streams on Twitch from time to time.

name: Erica Jong
bio: Erica Jong is an American novelist, satirist, and poet, known particularly for her 1973 novel Fear of Flying. The book became famously controversial for its attitudes towards female sexuality and figured prominently in the development of second-wave feminism.

name: Katell
bio: Katell is a fictional character played by Isabel Aimé González-Sola in the TV series "La Révolution". In the show, she works in the prison brigging goods to the convicts and starts a relation with Joseph Guillotin.

name: Sofia Seranno
bio: Sofia Serrano is a fictional character played by Penélope Cruz in the film Vanilla Sky. She's a dancer who meets David Aames at a party in Manhattan thanks to a friend. They spend the night together in Sofia's apartment.

name: Alice Walker
bio: Alice Walker is an American novelist, short story writer, poet, and social activist. In 1982, she wrote the novel The Color Purple, for which she won the National Book Award for hardcover fiction, and the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction. She also wrote the novels Meridian and The Third Life of Grange Copeland.

name: Joseph Losey
bio: Joseph Walton Losey III was an American theatre and film director, producer, and screenwriter. Born in Wisconsin, he studied in Germany with Bertolt Brecht and then returned to the United States.
job: American theatre director and film producer

name: Kalindi
bio: Rédac & chef de projet cinéma et séries télé pour le magazine MademoiZelle.
job: Rédac & chef de projet cinéma et séries télé

name: Johann Wolfgang von Goethe
bio: Johann Wolfgang von Goethe was a German writer and statesman. His works include: four novels; epic and lyric poetry; prose and verse dramas; memoirs; an autobiography; literary and aesthetic criticism; and treatises on botany, anatomy, and colour.

name: Beverly Sills
bio: Beverly Sills was an American operatic soprano whose peak career was between the 1950s and 1970s. Although she sang a repertoire from Handel and Mozart to Puccini, Massenet and Verdi, she was known for her performances in coloratura soprano roles in live opera and recordings.

name: Simone de Beauvoir
bio:
Simone Lucie Ernestine Marie Bertrand de Beauvoir was a French existentialist philosopher, writer, social theorist, and feminist activist. Though she did not consider herself a philosopher, nor was she considered one at the time of her death, she had a significant influence on both feminist existentialism and feminist theory.

- She was a French writer, philosopher, and feminist theorist who is best known for her seminal work "The Second Sex" published in 1949. This groundbreaking book analyzed the oppression of women in society and laid the foundation for modern feminism.

- Beauvoir was born in Paris in 1908 into a bourgeois family. She was raised Catholic but became an atheist at age 14.

- She studied at the University of Paris (Sorbonne) and passed the highly competitive agrégation exam in philosophy at the youngest possible age of 21, coming second only to her lifelong companion Jean-Paul Sartre.

- Beauvoir and Sartre had an unconventional open relationship for over 50 years, never marrying but remaining intellectual and romantic partners until Sartre's death in 1980.

- In addition to "The Second Sex", she wrote novels, memoirs, biographies and political treatises, often exploring existentialist themes. Her novel "The Mandarins" won France's prestigious Prix Goncourt in 1954.

- She was deeply involved in political activism, speaking out against the French colonial policies in Algeria and supporting feminist causes like the legalization of abortion in France.

- Beauvoir died in Paris in 1986 at age 78 and is buried next to Sartre in the Montparnasse Cemetery.
job: French existentialist philosopher, writer, and feminist activist

name: Lao Tzu
bio: Laozi, also rendered as Lao Tzu and Lao-Tze, was an ancient Chinese philosopher and writer. He is the reputed author of the Tao Te Ching, the founder of philosophical Taoism, and a deity in religious Taoism and traditional Chinese religions.

name: George Bernard Shaw
bio: George Bernard Shaw, known at his insistence simply as Bernard Shaw, was an Irish playwright, critic, polemicist and political activist. His influence on Western theatre, culture and politics extended from the 1880s to his death and beyond.

name: Oscar Wilde
bio: Oscar Fingal O'Flahertie Wills Wilde was an Irish poet and playwright. After writing in different forms throughout the 1880s, the early 1890s saw him become one of the most popular playwrights in London.

name: Dale Carnegie
bio: Dale Breckenridge Carnegie was an American writer and lecturer, and the developer of famous courses in self-improvement, salesmanship, corporate training, public speaking, and interpersonal skills.

name: Iris Simpkins
bio: Iris Simpkins is a fictional character issued by Kate Winslet in the film "The Holiday".

name: Jim Kwik
bio: He is the CEO and Founder of Kwik Learning, a leader in accelerated learning with online students of every age and vocation in over 150 countries.

name: Avis Amberg (fictional)
bio: Avis Amberg is a fictional character played by Patti LuPone in the TV miniseries "Hollywood". She plays the wife of Ace Amberg, the head of Ace Studios, and a former actress.

name: Zig Ziglar
bio: Hilary Hinton "Zig" Ziglar was an American author, salesman, and motivational speaker.

name: Gandhi
bio: Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi was an Indian lawyer, anti-colonial nationalist, and political ethicist, who employed nonviolent resistance to lead the successful campaign for India's independence from British Rule, and in turn inspire movements for civil rights and freedom across the world.

name: Lenore
bio: Lenore is the diplomat member of the Council of Sisters. She is in charge of subduing Hector.

name: George Eliot
bio: Mary Ann Evans, known by her pen name George Eliot, was an English novelist, poet, journalist, translator and one of the leading writers of the Victorian era.

name: Det. Ralph Anderson
bio: Detective Ralph Anderson is a fictional character played by Ben Mendelsohn in the TV miniseries The Outsider.

name: Socrates
bio: Socrates was a classical Greek philosopher credited as one of the founders of Western philosophy, and as being the first moral philosopher of the Western ethical tradition of thought.

name: Ben Frémont
bio: Ben Frémont is a fictional character in the french novel "Le parfum du bonheur est plus fort sous la pluie" in which he's Pauline's husband. They've a four years old children and try to navigate their relation's difficulties.

name: Jen Harding
bio: Jen Harding, is a fictional character played by Christina Applegate in the TV series Dead to Me. In the series, she's a realtor whose husband Ted was killed by a hit-and-run driver.

name: Harry Beltik

name: John W. Gardner
bio: John William Gardner, born on October 8, 1912, in Los Angeles, was a prominent figure in American politics and public service. He served as the Secretary of Health, Education, and Welfare under President Lyndon Johnson. Gardner was known for his advocacy for citizen participation and campaign finance reform, earning him the title "the father of campaign finance reform." He played a significant role in various initiatives, including the 1965 Elementary and Secondary Education Act and the enforcement of civil rights laws.
job: American politician, Former United States Secretary of Health, Education, and Welfare

name: Cyrus Albright
bio: Cyrus Albright is one of eight playable characters in Octopath Traveler. He is a professor at the Royal Academy located in Atlasdam, found in the Flatlands. Cyrus is known for caring greatly about knowledge and his passion for teaching.

name: Albert Einstein
bio: Albert Einstein was a German-born theoretical physicist who developed the theory of relativity, one of the two pillars of modern physics. His work is also known for its influence on the philosophy of science.

name: Chad Wiley
bio: Chad Wiley is a fictional character played by Patrick Sabongui in the streaming TV series "Firefly Lane". In the show, he's a college professor teaching journalism classes, and has Tully as a student.

name: J.P. Morgan
bio: John Pierpont Morgan Sr. was an American financier and banker who dominated corporate finance on Wall Street throughout the Gilded Age.

name: Isaac

ral Science Unit, is a fictional character in Mindhunter TV series.

name: Chiron
bio: In Greek mythology, Chiron was held to be the superlative centaur amongst his brethren since he was called the "wisest and justest of all the centaurs".

name: Patrick Bruel
bio:
Patrick Benguigui, born 14 May 1959), better known by his stage name Patrick Bruel, is a French singer-songwriter, actor and professional poker player.

His first success came as an actor, in 1979's Le Coup de sirocco. He continued acting in films, on television, and in the theater while pursuing his singing career. His first single, "Vide" ("Empty"), released in 1982, was not a success, but the follow-up, "Marre de cette nana-là" ("Fed up with that chick"), was a hit.
job: French singer-songwriter, actor, and poker player

name: Anaïs Nin
bio: Angela Anaïs Juana Antolina Rosa Edelmira Nin y Culmell, known professionally as Anaïs Nin was a French-Cuban American diarist, essayist, novelist, and writer of short stories and erotica. Born to Cuban parents in France, Nin was the daughter of composer Joaquín Nin and Rosa Culmell, a classically trained singer.

name: Richard Branson
bio: Sir Richard Charles Nicholas Branson is a British business magnate, investor, author and philanthropist. He founded the Virgin Group in the 1970s, which controls more than 400 companies in various fields. Branson expressed his desire to become an entrepreneur at a young age.

name: Serap

name: Han Solo

name: Edouard Philippe
bio: Édouard Charles Philippe is a French politician serving as Prime Minister of France since 15 May 2017 under President Emmanuel Macron. A lawyer by occupation, Philippe is a former member of the Union for a Popular Movement, which later became The Republicans.

name: Ryo Saeba
bio:
Ryo Saeba (冴羽獠, Saeba Ryo) is a sweeper in Tokyo and the main character of the City Hunter series.

At the age of three, Ryo was the only survivor of a plane crash in Central America. He was raised as a guerilla fighter and has no knowledge of his prior identity. After the war, Ryo makes his way to the United States, before eventually moving to Tokyo.

name: Joey Tribbiani
bio: Joey Tribbiani is an actor and food enthusiast, known for his role on Days of Our Lives.

bio: Quality strip cartoon for whole family since 2001. Director of collection (#Octopus éditions Delcourt).

name: Zeus
bio: Zeus is the sky and thunder god in ancient Greek religion, who rules as king of the gods of Mount Olympus. His name is cognate with the first element of his Roman equivalent Jupiter.

name: Thomas Hora
bio: Thomas Hora is considered the founder of the discipline of metapsychiatry, an attempt to integrate principles from metaphysics, spirituality, and psychology.

name: Y-Vonne Hutchinson
bio: Former international human rights lawyer. Lover of planes, puppies, pie and Studs Terkel.

bio:
He's the author of «Observer les oiseaux de la baie du Mont-Saint-Michel».

He's done 16 years as a research officer and animator. He then  launched "Birding Mont-Saint-Michel" in 2018, a structure specializing in guided outings in Normandy and Brittany.

bio: Maghla is a french Twitch streamer. She plays various video games including adventure, FPS (First Person Shooter) or horror. Her streams contain also manual craft and cooking amoung other activites.

name: William of Ockham
bio: English Franciscan friar, scholastic philosopher, and theologian, who is believed to have been born in Ockham, a small village in Surrey.

name: Alfred Hitchcock
bio: Sir Alfred Joseph Hitchcock KBE was an English film director, screenwriter, producer and editor. He is widely regarded as one of the most influential figures in the history of cinema. In a career spanning six decades, he directed over 50 feature films, many of which are still widely watched and studied today.

name: Nicoll Hunt
bio: Creator of FIST OF AWESOME and co-creator of BREW TOWN & MAXIMUM CAR. More beard than man. He/him.

name: Alfred, Lord Tennyson
bio: Alfred Tennyson, 1st Baron Tennyson FRS was a British poet. He was the Poet Laureate during much of Queen Victoria's reign and remains one of the most popular British poets. In 1829, Tennyson was awarded the Chancellor's Gold Medal at Cambridge for one of his first pieces, "Timbuktu".

name: Jim Preston
bio: Jim Preston is a fictional character played by Chris Pratt in the film "Passengers". In the film, he's a mechanical engineer who wakes up 90 years too early on a sleeper ship transporting 5,000 colonists and 258 crew members in hibernation pods. The ship is travelling from Earth to the planet Homestead II.

name: Bill Cosby
bio: William Henry Cosby Jr. is an American stand-up comedian, actor, musician, author, and convicted sex offender. Cosby began his career as a stand-up comic at the hungry i in San Francisco during the 1960s.

name: Narrator
bio: The narrator in the video game "Little Hope" tells part of the story to the player and help to understand what happened.

name: Ben Wood
bio: Ben Wood is a fictional character played by James Marsden in the TV series Dead to Me. He's Steve's semi-identical twin brother and Jen's new love interest who is a chiropractor.

name: Viktor E. Frankl
bio: Viktor Emil Frankl was an Austrian neurologist and psychiatrist as well as a Holocaust survivor, surviving Theresienstadt, Kaufering and Türkheim.

name: Donald Norman
bio:
Donald Norman is an American researcher, professor, and author who is widely regarded as a pioneer in the fields of design, usability engineering, and cognitive science. Here are some key facts about him:

📕 • He is best known for his book "The Design of Everyday Things", which advocates for user-centered design principles and explores how design impacts our ability to interact with everyday objects and technologies.

🍎 • He coined the term "User Experience Architect" when he joined Apple in 1993, making him the first person to have "User Experience" in his job title. This helped establish and popularize the field of user experience (UX) design.

🏛️ • He co-founded the Nielsen Norman Group, a leading consulting firm in the user experience field, along with Jakob Nielsen.

🎙️ • He has served on numerous advisory boards and committees, including at Motorola, Toyota, TED Conference, Panasonic, and Encyclopædia Britannica, contributing his expertise in design and human-computer interaction.

🎖️ • He received the prestigious Benjamin Franklin Medal in Computer and Cognitive Science in 2006 for his pioneering work in the field of user-centered design.

🤓 • In 2011, he was elected as a member of the National Academy of Engineering for developing design principles based on human cognition that enhance human-technology interaction.

🚀 • He advocates that while academics can refine existing products, it is technologists who accomplish major breakthroughs and innovations in product design.

name: Ava Silva
bio: Ava Silva is a fictionnal character played by Alba Baptista in the TV series Warrior Nun.

name: Nick Carraway
bio: Nick Carraway is a fictional character and narrator in F. Scott Fitzgerald's The Great Gatsby (1925).  In the 2013 film, he is  a would-be writer, Gatsby's friend, and the film's narrator.

name: Albert Einstein
bio: German-born theoretical physicist who developed the theory of relativity, one of the two pillars of modern physics.

name: V
bio: V is a mercenary and the main character in the video game Cyberpunk 2077.

name: Mary Morrison
bio: Mary Morrison is a successful author of thriller novels in the film "Deadly illusions". The character is played by Kristin Davis.

name: Virginia Woolf
bio: Adeline Virginia Woolf was an English writer, considered one of the most important modernist 20th-century authors and also a pioneer in the use of stream of consciousness as a narrative device. Woolf was born into an affluent household in South Kensington, London, the seventh child in a blended family of eight.

name: Charles de Montargis
bio: Charles de Montargis is a fictional character played by Laurent Lucas in the TV series "La Révolution". In the show he's Elise's uncle and Donatien father. He has a manipulator mind and doesn't have a high esteem of other  people.

name: George Addair
bio: George Washington Adair was a real-estate developer in post Civil War Atlanta.

name: Farrah Gray
bio: Farrah Gray is an American businessman, investor, author, columnist, and motivational speaker. Gray was raised on Chicago's South side. He began his entrepreneurial career at the age of six selling homemade lotion and hand-painted rocks door-to-door.

name: Etoiles
bio: Étoiles is a french Twitch streamer. He's mostly known for his culture streams and his high skills in video games, notably on Super Smash Bros. He regularly co-host "The Night of Culture" with Samuel Etienne, the television host of "Questions pour un champion".

name: Sigmund Freud
bio: Sigmund Freud was an Austrian neurologist and the founder of psychoanalysis, a clinical method for treating psychopathology through dialogue between a patient and a psychoanalyst. Freud was born to Galician Jewish parents in the Moravian town of Freiberg, in the Austrian Empire.

name: Forest officer 1
bio: This forest guard was doing a night walk on his horse but encounters Marianne. He appears on season 1 chapter 6, around the time code: 14:00.

name: Abraham Lincoln
bio: Abraham Lincoln was an American statesman and lawyer who served as the 16th president of the United States from March 1861 until his assassination in April 1865. Lincoln led the nation through the American Civil War, its bloodiest war and its greatest moral, constitutional, and political crisis.

name: Shigeru Miyamoto
bio: Shigeru Miyamoto is a Japanese video game designer and producer at Nintendo, where he serves as one of its representative directors. He is the creator of some of the most acclaimed and best-selling game franchises of all time, such as Mario and The Legend of Zelda.

name: Edgar Allan Poe
bio: Edgar Allan Poe was an American writer, poet, editor, and literary critic. Poe is best known for his poetry and short stories, particularly his tales of mystery and the macabre.

name: Dave Amari
bio: Dave Amari is a fictional character played by Ennis Esmer in the TV series "You Me Her". In the show, he's one of the Trakarsky's neighbors and Jack's best friend.

name: Charles Kuralt
bio: Charles Bishop Kuralt was an American journalist. He is most widely known for his long career with CBS, first for his "On the Road" segments on The CBS Evening News with Walter Cronkite, and later as the first anchor of CBS News Sunday Morning, a position he held for fifteen years.

name: Thomas Howard, Duke of Norfolk
bio: Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk KG PC, was a prominent English politician and nobleman of the Tudor era. He was an uncle of two of the wives of King Henry VIII, namely Anne Boleyn and Catherine Howard, both of whom were beheaded, and played a major role in the machinations affecting these royal marriages. In the film "The Other Boleyn Girl" he is played by David Morrissey.

name: Gloria Steinem
bio: Gloria Marie Steinem is an American feminist, journalist, and social political activist who became nationally recognized as a leader and a spokeswoman for the American feminist movement in the late 1960s and early 1970s. Steinem was a columnist for New York magazine, and a co-founder of Ms. magazine.

name: Charles Swindoll
bio: Charles Rozell "Chuck" Swindoll is an evangelical Christian pastor, author, educator, and radio preacher. He founded Insight for Living, headquartered in Frisco, Texas, which airs a radio program of the same name on more than 2,000 stations around the world in 15 languages.

name: Antonio Damasio
bio: Antonio Damasio is a Portuguese-American neuroscientist. He is currently the David Dornsife Chair in Neuroscience, as well as Professor of Psychology, Philosophy, and Neurology, at the University of Southern California, and, additionally, an adjunct professor at the Salk Institute.

name: Ralph Waldo Emerson
bio: Ralph Waldo Emerson was an American essayist, lecturer, philosopher, and poet who led the transcendentalist movement of the mid-19th century.

name: Norman Vaughan
bio: Norman Edward Vaughan was an English comedian who led a long and successful career in the television and theatre, appearing occasionally in films.

name: Queen
bio: Queen are a British rock band formed in London in 1970 by Freddie Mercury (lead vocals, piano), Brian May (guitar, vocals), and Roger Taylor (drums, vocals), later joined by John Deacon (bass). Their earliest works were influenced by progressive rock, hard rock, and heavy metal, but the band gradually ventured into more conventional and radio-friendly works by incorporating further styles, such as arena rock and pop rock.

name: Adam (old)
bio: Adam is a fictional character played by Dietrich Hollinderbäumer in the TV series "Dark". This character refers to an old and disfigured Adam. He's also the leader of Sic Mundus.

name: Nina's grandfather
bio: Nina's grandfather comes to Japan with his granddaughter, as she has her pianist concert.

name: Norman Vincent Peale
bio: Norman Vincent Peale was an American minister and author known for his work in popularizing the concept of positive thinking, especially through his best-selling book The Power of Positive Thinking.

name: Leonardo da Vinci
bio: Leonardo di ser Piero da Vinci, known as Leonardo da Vinci, was an Italian polymath of the Renaissance whose areas of interest included invention, drawing, painting, sculpture, architecture, science, music, mathematics, engineering, literature, anatomy, geology, astronomy, botany, paleontology, and cartography.

name: Jonathan Kozol
bio: Jonathan Kozol is an American writer, educator, and activist, best known for his books on public education in the United States.

name: Chikaro
bio: Chikaro is a japanese researcher who has a conversation with Maëlle in a forest in Nepal.

name: Cédric Ingrand
bio: Cédric Ingrand is a french journalist working in the field of Internet and technologies. He hosts "Plein Écran" on the french channel LCI.  he also takes part in various prpgrams such as "Les coulisses de l'économie" on TF1, "Le Rendez-vous Tech" or "On Refait le Mac".

name: St. Jean-Baptiste-Marie Vianney
bio: Jean-Baptiste-Marie Vianney, T.O.S.F., commonly known in English as Saint John Vianney, was a French parish priest who is venerated in the Catholic Church as a saint and as the patron saint of parish priests.

name: Reynolds Woodcock
bio: Reynolds Woodcock is a fictional character played by Daniel Day-Lewis in the film Phantom Thread. In the film, he creates dresses for members of high society, even royalty. His clients view him as a genius whose creations enable them to become their best selves; but his creativity and charm are matched by his obsessive and controlling personality.

name: Jesus
bio: Jesus, also referred to as Jesus of Nazareth or Jesus Christ, was a first-century Jewish preacher and religious leader. He is the central figure of Christianity. Most Christians believe he is the incarnation of God the Son and the awaited Messiah (the Christ) prophesied in the Old Testament.

name: Arthur Ashe
bio: Arthur Robert Ashe Jr. was an American professional tennis player who won three Grand Slam titles. Ashe was the first black player selected to the United States Davis Cup team and the only black man ever to win the singles title at Wimbledon, the US Open, and the Australian Open. He retired in 1980.

name: Travis
bio: Travis is a widower whose daughter goes to the same school as Marah and finds a connection with Kate

name: Roger Staubach
bio: Roger Thomas Staubach, nicknamed "Roger the Dodger", "Captain America" and "Captain Comeback", is an American former professional football player who was a quarterback for the Dallas Cowboys in the National Football League.

name: Mary Whitney
bio: Mary Whitney is a fictional character, a maid, and friend of Grace Marks. Mary believes in herself and in Canada as a place that a hard working girl can earn her way. She plans to save her wages for a dowry so she can marry a farmer and be mistress of her own home. She's played by  Rebecca Liddiard in the miniserie.

name: Albus Dumbledore
bio: Prof. Albus Percival Wulfric Brian Dumbledor is a fictional character in the Harry Potter series of novels by J. K. Rowling. For most of the series, he is the headmaster of the wizarding school Hogwarts. As part of his backstory, it is revealed that he is the founder and leader of the Order of the Phoenix, an organisation dedicated to fighting the Dark wizard Lord Voldemort.

name: Billy Alsbrooks
bio: Billy Alsbrooks, Jr., better known by his stage name White Dawg, is an American rapper and record producer.

name: Herbert Zucker
bio: Herbert Zucker is a fictional character played by Steve Witting in the TV miniseries The Outsider. He is a psychologist who has the detective Ralph as a patient.

name: Claude Bolton
bio: Claude Bolton is a fictional character played by Paddy Considine in the TV miniseries The Outsider. He's a bouncer at the Peach Crease night club.

name: Dan Broderick
bio: Dan Broderick is a fictional character played by Christian Slater in the TV series "Dirty Jonh". In the show, he's a lawyer specialized in pursuing medical malpactrices. He's married to Betty and has four children.

name: Joseph Ignace Guillotin
bio: Joseph Ignace Guillotin is a fictional character played by Amir El Kacem in the TV series "La Révolution". In the shows, he's a physician (medical doctor) investigating mysterious deaths and disparitions. Although fictional, this character truly existed between 28 May 1738 – 26 March 1814.

name: Esty
bio: Esther "Esty" Shapiro is a fictional character played by Shira Haas in the miniseries "Unorthodox". In the miniseries, she's a 19-year-old Jewish woman who runs away from her arranged marriage and Ultra-Orthodox community in Williamsburg, Brooklyn, New York City. She moves to Berlin, where her estranged mother lives, and tries to navigate a secular life and take classes at a music conservatory.

name: Vasily Borgov
bio: Vasily Borgov is a fictional character played by Marcin Dorociński in the TV miniseries The Queen's Gambit. In the show, he's the current Soviet-Russian world champion chess player and Beth's strongest competitor.

name: Mahatma Gandhi
bio: Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi was an Indian lawyer, anti-colonial nationalist, and political ethicist, who employed nonviolent resistance to lead the successful campaign for India's independence from British Rule, and in turn inspire movements for civil rights and freedom across the world.

name: Maxence
bio: Maxence is a fictional character played by Jérémie Covillault in the TV series "La Révolution". In the show, he's a priest close to Joseph Guillotin and he believes that everyone deserves to be saved.

name: Vincent van Gogh
bio: Vincent Willem van Gogh was a Dutch post-impressionist painter who is among the most famous and influential figures in the history of Western art. In just over a decade, he created about 2,100 artworks, including around 860 oil paintings, most of which date from the last two years of his life.

name: Gus Mancuso
bio: Gus Mancuso is a fictional character played by  Laurence Fishburne in the film "Passengers". He plays as the chief deck officer on the Avalon and helps to repair the ship.

name: Kobe Bryant
bio: Kobe Bean Bryant was an American professional basketball player. As a shooting guard, Bryant entered the National Basketball Association directly from high school, and played his entire 20-season professional career in the league with the Los Angeles Lakers.

name: Jim Rohn
bio: Emanuel James Rohn professionally known as Jim Rohn, was an American entrepreneur, author and motivational speaker.

name: Satya Nadell
bio: Satya Narayana Nadella is an engineer and Indian American business executive. He is the chief executive officer of Microsoft, succeeding Steve Ballmer in 2014. He led a giant round of layoffs and flattened the organization, getting rid of middle managers.

name: Jeremiah Pontelli
bio: Jeremiah Pontelli is a fictional character. Jeremiah the peddler, alias Geraldo Ponti, magician, alias Dr. Jerome DuPont, "Neuro-Hypnotist", first met Grace when she was a new housemaid and he was peddling house to house in Toronto. When he called at the Kinnear house, he told her he feared she might be in danger there. He's played by Zachari Levi.

name: Sébastien Frit
bio: Sébastien Frit, plus connu sous le pseudonyme Seb la Frite ou SEB, est un vidéaste français. En août 2018, il est le treizième youtubeur francophone le plus suivi, avec plus de 4 millions d'abonnés pour environ 468 millions de vues.

name: Donatien de Montargis
bio: Donatien de Montargis is a fictional character played by Julien Frison in the TV series "La Révolution". In the show, he's Charles' son and has a terrible disease. He's impulsive and seek his father admiration.

name: Anais Nin
bio: Angela Anaïs Juana Antolina Rosa Edelmira Nin y Culmell, known professionally as Anaïs Nin was a French-Cuban American diarist, essayist, novelist, and writer of short stories and erotica. Born to Cuban parents in France, Nin was the daughter of composer Joaquín Nin and Rosa Culmell, a classically trained singer.

name: Adrian Veildt
bio: Adrian Veildt is a fictional character in the 2019 TV series Watchmen, played by Jeremy Irons. He's a former businessman and the vigilante Ozymandias, the "smartest man in the world". He is now living as an aristocratic lord of a country manor that turned out to be on Europa.

name: William "Bill" Farrah (FANGS)
bio: Bill Farrah is a character in the TV series «A Murder at the End of the World». He's an artist under the name FANGS.

name: Napoléon Bonaparte
bio: Napoleon Bonaparte was a French statesman and military leader who led many successful campaigns during the French Revolution and the French Revolutionary Wars, and was Emperor of the French from 1804 until 1814 and again briefly in 1815 during the Hundred Days.

name: Ned Stark
bio: Ned Stark is the head of House Stark, Lord of Winterfell, and Warden of the North.

name: Maimonides
bio: Moses ben Maimon, commonly known as Maimonides and also referred to by the acronym Rambam, was a medieval Sephardic Jewish philosopher who became one of the most prolific and influential Torah scholars of the Middle Ages. In his time, he was also a preeminent astronomer and physician.

name: Albert Einstein & Leopold Infeld
bio: Albert Einstein was a German-born theoretical physicist who developed the theory of relativity, one of the two pillars of modern physics. Leopold Infeld was a Polish physicist who worked mainly in Poland and Canada.

name: Blaise Pascal
bio: Blaise Pascal was a French mathematician, physicist, inventor, writer and Catholic theologian. He was a child prodigy who was educated by his father, a tax collector in Rouen.

name: Les Brown
bio: Leslie Calvin "Les" Brown is an American motivational speaker, author, former radio DJ, and former television host. He was a member of the Ohio House of Representatives from 1976 to 1981. As a motivational speaker, he uses the catch phrase "it's possible!" to encourage people to follow their dreams.

name: Richard Feynman
bio: American theoretical physicist, known for his work in the path integral formulation of quantum mechanics, the theory of quantum electrodynamics, and the physics of the superfluidity of supercooled liquid helium, as well as in particle physics for which he proposed the parton model.

name: Jane Margolis & Yasmin Kafai
bio: Jane's research focuses on equity in education and how fields become segregated. Yasmin's work empowers students to use computer programming to design games, electronic textiles, and biological applications to promote coding, crafting, and creativity across grades K–16.

name: Stephen Fry
bio: Stephen John Fry is an English actor, comedian and writer. He and Hugh Laurie are the comic double act Fry and Laurie, who starred in A Bit of Fry & Laurie and Jeeves and Wooster.

name: Anatole France
bio: Anatole France was a French poet, journalist, and novelist with several best-sellers. Ironic and skeptical, he was considered in his day the ideal French man of letters.

name: Christian Longo
bio: Christian Michael Longo is a convicted murderer who committed his crimes in the U.S. state of Oregon. Originating from Ypsilanti Township, Michigan, he married Mary Jane Baker at age 19 and they had three children together. He and his family often encountered financial difficulties due to his reckless spending habits.

name: Anonymous
bio: A anonymous person who doesn't want to be known.

name: Inspector Ronan
bio: Fictional character in the TV series 'Marianne'. He's charged to investigate on the deaths of some citizens.

name: Sue Snell
bio: Susan D. Snell is a fictional character created by American author Stephen King in his first published 1974 horror novel, Carrie. She is a popular teenage girl dating Tommy Ross. After tormenting Carrie White in the locker room, Sue begins to feel remorse for her actions.

name: Nikola Tesla
bio:
Nikola Tesla was a Serbian-American inventor, electrical engineer, mechanical engineer, and futurist who is best known
 for his contributions to the design of the modern alternating current electricity supply system.

name: Maïté “Eskarina”
bio: Rédac' Chef @KissMyGeek - Podcasteuse @SuperGamerside et RDV Jeux - Chef de Projet IRL.

name: Tenzin Gyatso
bio: The 14th Dalai Lama, known to the Tibetan people as Gyalwa Rinpoche, is, as the incumbent Dalai Lama, the highest spiritual leader and head of Tibet. He is considered a living Bodhisattva; specifically, an emanation of Avalokiteśvara in Sanskrit, and Chenrezig in Tibetan.

name: Molière
bio: Jean-Baptiste Poquelin, known by his stage name Molière, was a French playwright, actor and poet, widely regarded as one of the greatest writers in the French language and universal literature. His extant works include comedies, farces, tragicomedies, comédie-ballets and more.

name: Bruce Lee
bio: Hong Kong-American actor, director, martial artist, martial arts instructor, and philosopher.

name: Simon Sinek
bio: Simon Oliver Sinek is a British-American author, motivational speaker and organizational consultant. He is the author of five books, including Start With Why.

name: Amelia Earhart
bio: Amelia Mary Earhart was an American aviation pioneer and author. Earhart was the first female aviator to fly solo across the Atlantic Ocean. She set many other records, wrote best-selling books about her flying experiences, and was instrumental in the formation of The Ninety-Nines, an organization for female pilots.

name: Jamie Paolinetti
bio: Jamie Paolinetti is a professional filmmaker and Artistic Director of The Atwater Playhouse.

name: Guy de Montargis
bio: Guy de Montargis is a fictional character played by Pierre Aussedat in the TV series "La Révolution". In the show, he's Elise's father, and has the highest nobility title.

name: Arthur C. Clarke
bio: Sir Arthur Charles Clarke CBE FRAS was a British science fiction writer, science writer and futurist, inventor, undersea explorer, and television series host. He co-wrote the screenplay for the 1968 film 2001: A Space Odyssey, one of the most influential films of all time.

name: Ratched
bio: Nurse Mildred Ratched is a fictional character played by Sarah Paulson in the TV series "Ratched". In the show, she's a nurse hired by Dr. Hanover to work at Lucia State Hospital. But she has other motive.

name: Emmanuel Macron
bio: Emmanuel Jean-Michel Frédéric Macron born 21 December 1977 is a French politician who has been serving as the 25th president of France since 2017 and ex officio one of the two Co-Princes of Andorra. He previously was Minister of Economics, Industry and Digital Affairs under President François Hollande from 2014 to 2016 and Deputy Secretary-General to the President from 2012 to 2014. He has been a member of Renaissance since he founded it in 2016.

name: Grace Marks
bio: Grace Marks (c. July 1828 – after c. 1873) was an Irish-Canadian maid who was involved in the 1843 murder of her employer Thomas Kinnear and his housekeeper, Nancy Montgomery, in Richmond Hill, Ontario. Her conviction for the murder of Kinnear was controversial and sparked much debate about whether Marks was actually instrumental in the murder or merely an unwitting accessory. Marks was the subject of Margaret Atwood's historical fiction novel Alias Grace and its adaptations in other media.

name: Klô Pelgag
bio: Klô Pelgag is the stage name of Chloé Pelletier-Gagnon, a Canadian singer-songwriter from Quebec. Beginning her career in 2009 as a performer at various festivals and music contests in Quebec, she released her self-titled debut EP in 2012. Her full-length album L'Alchimie des monstres followed in 2013.

name: Charles Chaplin
bio:
Sir Charles Spencer Chaplin KBE was an English comic actor, filmmaker, and composer who rose to fame in the era of silent film. He became a worldwide icon through his screen persona, the Tramp, and is considered one of the film industry's most important figures. His career spanned more than 75 years, from childhood in the Victorian era until a year before his death in 1977, and encompassed both adulation and controversy.

- Charles Chaplin (1889-1977) was an English comic actor, filmmaker, and composer who rose to fame in the era of silent film with his iconic "Tramp" character.

- He was a pioneering filmmaker who acted in, directed, produced, edited, and composed the music for most of his films. Some of his most famous works include The Kid (1921), The Gold Rush (1925), City Lights (1931), Modern Times (1936), and The Great Dictator (1940).

- Chaplin had a very difficult childhood marked by poverty and hardship. His mother was committed to a mental asylum when he was young, and he was sent to a workhouse twice before age 9.

- He began performing on stage at a very young age, making his first amateur appearance at age 5.[1] By age 26, he had become one of the highest paid people in the world with a contract for $670,000 per year.

- Chaplin composed the scores and songs for several of his films, including the popular songs "Smile" from Modern Times and "This Is My Song" from A Countess from Hong Kong. He won an Academy Award for Best Original Score for Limelight in 1973.

- He was married four times, including three marriages to teenagers when he was much older. His turbulent personal life, political views, and marriages to young women caused scandals.

- Chaplin was a perfectionist who would do hundreds of takes to get a scene right. For City Lights, he made an actress repeat just two words ("Flower, sir") 342 times.

- He co-founded the movie studio United Artists in 1919 with Douglas Fairbanks, Mary Pickford, and D.W. Griffith as a way to maintain creative control over their films.
job: Iconic English comic actor and filmmaker

name: Dribbble
bio: Dribbble is a self-promotion and social networking platform for digital designers and creatives. It serves as a design portfolio platform, jobs and recruiting site and is one of the largest platforms for designers to share their work online. The company is fully remote with no headquarters.

name: Satoshi Nakamoto
bio:
Here are some key facts about Satoshi Nakamoto, the pseudonymous creator of Bitcoin:

- Satoshi Nakamoto is not a real name, but rather a pseudonym used by the unknown person or group who created Bitcoin.

- They published the Bitcoin white paper in October 2008, outlining the concept of a decentralized peer-to-peer electronic cash system.

- In January 2009, Nakamoto released the first Bitcoin software and mined the first block of bitcoins, known as the "genesis block."

- Nakamoto communicated with early Bitcoin developers through online forums and email until around 2010, after which they disappeared from public view.

- Their true identity remains a mystery, with various theories speculating that Nakamoto could be an individual like Nick Szabo or Hal Finney, or even a group of developers.

- Nakamoto is estimated to have mined around 1 million bitcoins, which would be worth billions of dollars today, but this stash has remained untouched.

- In 2015, Nakamoto was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Economics for their contributions to the creation of Bitcoin.

- Despite numerous claims by individuals like Craig Wright, no one has provided conclusive evidence of being the real Satoshi Nakamoto.

- The reasons for Nakamoto's anonymity are unknown, but it aligns with Bitcoin's decentralized principles and may have been for privacy and security.
job: Pseudonymous person or persons who developed Bitcoin

name: Guillaume Apollinaire

name: Sophocles
bio:
Sophocles (c. 497/496 – winter 406/405 BC) was an ancient Greek tragedian, known as one of three from whom at least one play has survived in full. Sophocles wrote over 120 plays, but only seven have survived in a complete form: Ajax, Antigone, Women of Trachis, Oedipus Rex, Electra, Philoctetes, and Oedipus at Colonus. 

For almost fifty years, Sophocles was the most celebrated playwright in the dramatic competitions of the city-state of Athens which took place during the religious festivals of the Lenaea and the Dionysia. He competed in thirty competitions, won twenty-four, and was never judged lower than second place. Aeschylus won thirteen competitions, and was sometimes defeated by Sophocles; Euripides won four.

Originally first in line to Mufasa's throne until he is suddenly replaced by Mufasa's son Simba, Scar decides to lead an army of hyenas in his plot to take the throne by killing Mufasa and Simba, who escapes into exile, ultimately blaming his brother's death on his nephew.

It is one of the world's best known books and has been the basis for several plays and films.

Monáe has a mezzo-soprano voice. Her musical styles have been described as "a soaring orchestral trip enlivened with blockbuster vocals, mysterious imagery and notes of Sixties pop and jazz". More succintly: R&B, Pop, Funk, Psychedelic, Soul.
